- Do not localize your revision pass to only the sections explicitly cited by the analyzer; you must perform your own repo-grounded analysis before finalizing.
- Build a closure ledger before finalizing the revised draft. At minimum, account for (1) each analyzer-cited issue, (2) the adjacent or implied issues your own analysis discovered, (3) the exact revised sections that close each issue, and (4) any dependent sections that must also change for the plan to become coherent.
- Use this shared defect vocabulary in both analysis findings and replanning fixes: Explicit requirement missing, Implied core workflow missing, Prerequisite action/state missing, Verification gap, Repository reference invalid, Cross-section inconsistency, Executor research burden. Assign a stable ID to every gap you report and preserve that ID in the corresponding fix entry.
- Classify the defect scope as `local_section`, `cross_section`, or `repo_wide` before deciding what to preserve. The classification is diagnostic only and does not permit a localized repair if your own repo-grounded analysis reveals broader issues.
- When the ORIGINAL REQUEST imposes repo-wide structural rules, build a repo-wide inventory for every rule category those requirements cover instead of deriving scope only from the first failing example.
- Re-run enough repo-grounded analysis yourself to discover additional rejectable issues beyond the analyzer's cited list before deciding the draft is ready; if your runtime provides a subagent mechanism, fan out read-only scouts to verify each analyzer finding's closure and review from independent angles, otherwise run the same checks sequentially yourself.
- This continuation exists because the prior planning pass failed. If your runtime provides a subagent gate, you MUST use it as a hard stop against the plan-quality rubric and your replanning self-audit; until a subagent review reports no remaining rubric-grounded findings, you MUST NOT finalize or submit the revised plan artifact.
- Infer the core user-facing workflows and prerequisite actions that must exist for the ORIGINAL REQUEST to count as working, even when the prompt states them only implicitly.
- If the defect scope is `repo_wide`, replace the summary, scope, and early steps so Step 1 becomes repo-wide discovery before narrowing to specific files; do not preserve the prior target cluster as the starting scope.
- Do not edit `.agent/artifacts/plan.json` directly. If fixing one section changes the truth of another section, replace every dependent section in the same draft so the finalized plan is internally consistent.
- Do not finalize a draft that still has any known unresolved analyzer finding, even if some sections improved. Prefer a full atomic replacement over piecemeal repair when that is the simplest way to restore global coherence.
